Wisdom is needed by those who wander far and wide;
what is pumped at home;
in an instant
he who does not know and sits with his snot.

A foolish man thinks everyone is a friendly friend;
he meets a father, although few read about him,
if he sits with his friends.

A foolish man thinks everyone is a friendly friend;
then he finds, when he comes to the assembly,
that he has few to say.

A foolish man, who comes with age,
it is best that he be silent;
no one knows that he cannot,
unless he speaks much;
A man knows, the wise man knows,
though he speaks much.

A man should endure the need of his cattle,
which he has obtained;
often he spares the suffering, that he has a sweet heart;
many things go worse than they last.

With weapons and dangers, friends shall rejoice;
that which is seen in themselves;
The giver and the receiver are friends for the longest time,
if it is to be well.

A man shall be a friend to his friend
and repay gift for gift;
Laughter for laughter should be accepted, but slander for lies.

A man should be a friend to his own friend,
and to them also;
but no man should be a friend to his enemy.

I gave my vows to
two wooden men;
it seemed to me that they had torn;
none is a tree of gloom.

Small sands of small seas
small are the minds of the wise;
for all men became equally wise;
half is an age where.

The average man's snore is every man;
life to snore is;
those who live best,
who know much.

The average man's snore is every man,
life to snore is;
for the snore man's heart
is seldom glad,
if he is always snore,
who is.

He who has his kingdom in moderation shall manage his affairs;
then he finds that which comes with boldness
that no one is too hasty.

The night becomes happy who is faithful to the food,
shames the ship's row;
the autumn's gloom disappears;
more weather is in five days
than more in a month.

No man should ever love another;
often get on the sly, which on the foolish nor get,
beautiful colors.

Know that another man must,
this is what many go through;
foolishness from slyness makes the son of the sly make a difference in the power.

The mind alone knows that which lives near the heart,
one who sees too much;
nothing is sicker than a man who is sly than to see nothing to love.

That I then experienced, when I sat in the reed,
and the weight of my difference;
flesh and heart were in my sly maiden;
I endured her to be more honorable.

I found the maiden of Billings lying on a bed of sun-white;
the earl's love seemed to me to be
except with that kind of life.

Many are good maidens, if they dare to know,
with a tail;
then I tried that, when the plan
I stretched out on the flowing stream;
whose scorn sought me the cruel man,
and I had the knowledge of that.

At home a cheerful fellow and with guests a quarrel,
shall be about himself, small and talkative,
if he wants to be well-versed,
often shall have good things to say;
fimbulfambi is called, he who can say little,
that is the chief of no use.

I am sure that I would still have come
from the giants' gardens,
if I Gunnlad nor use,
the good wife,
of those whom I laid my arm over.

The matter is to cast spells on the throne of Urðarbrunn, I saw and kept quiet, I saw and kept quiet, I listened to the words of men; I heard too runes judge, nor too silent counsels Háva held at, Háva held in, I heard him say thus: 112. We advise you, Loddfáfnir, but you learn counsel, - you would enjoy it if you do, you would be well if you can -: at night you rise unless you are on guard, or you look inside yourself out of place. 113. We advise you, Loddfáfnir, but you learn counsel, - you would enjoy it if you do, you would be well if you can -: you shall sleep in the arms of a woman of many talents, so that she may be able to join you. 114. She does so, that you do not listen
to the assembly or the people's speech;
if you eat want-to or human pleasure,
you go to sleep sorrowful.

Then the two are mixed, who speaks with all his heart;
everything is better than to be in a quarrel;
is he a friend to another who wants one thing.

We will not grant me happiness nor with the horned;
I went down, I took up runes,
I took up, I fell back from there.

Nine fiddle-stories I took
from the famous son of Bölþorn, Bestla's father,
and I drank of the gate's expensive mead, the dew of Óðrer.

I know that for the eighteenth time,
when I have ever known a virgin or a man's wife,
- all is better, which one too knows;
that follows the end of poetry, -
except for one, which is worse than me,
or my sister is.
